06147nam a22007935i 9781400883042DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2016    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008830427 a10.1515/97814008830422doi  a(DE-B1597)474643  a(OCoLC)959278151  a(OCoLC)984688485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB2521b.H67 2018 7aHIS0140002bisacsh 7aPHI0000002bisacsh 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a1932231 aHösle, Vittorio, eauthor.12aA Short History of German Philosophy /cVittorio Hösle. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Note -- tPreface to the English Translation -- t1. Does German Philosophy Have a History? And Has There Ever Been a "German Spirit"? -- t2. The Birth of God in the Soul: The Beginnings of German-language Philosophizing in the Middle Ages in the Work of Meister Eckhart and Nicholas of Cusa's Consummation and Demolition of Medieval Thought -- t3. The Change in the Philosophical Situation Brought about by the Reformation: Paracelsus's New Natural Philosophy and the "No" in Jakob Böhme's God -- t4. Only the Best Is Good Enough for God: Leibniz's Synthesis of Scholasticism and the New Science -- t5. The German Ethical Revolution: Immanuel Kant -- t6. The Human Sciences as a Religious Duty: Lessing, Hamann, Herder, Schiller, the Early Romantics, and Wilhelm von Humboldt -- t7. The Longing for a System: German Idealism -- t8. The Revolt against Christian Dogmatics: Schopenhauer's Discovery of the Indian World -- t9. The Revolt against the Bourgeois World: Ludwig Feuerbach and Karl Marx -- t10. The Revolt against Universalistic Morals: Friedrich Nietzsche -- t11. The Exact Sciences as a Challenge and the Rise of Analytic Philosophy: Frege, the Viennese and Berlin Circles, Wittgenstein -- t12. The Search for a Foundation of the Human Sciences and the Social Sciences in Neo- Kantianism and Dilthey, and Husserl's Exploration of Consciousness -- t13. Is Philosophy Partly to Blame for the German Catastrophe? Heidegger between Fundamental Ontology and History of Being -- t14. National Socialist Anthropology and Political Philosophy: Arnold Gehlen and Carl Schmitt -- t15. The Federal Republic's Adaptation to Western European Normality: Gadamer, the Two Frankfurt Schools, and Hans Jonas -- t16. Why We Cannot Assume That There Will Continue to Be a German Philosophy -- tIndex of Names  aThis concise but comprehensive book provides an original history of German-language philosophy from the Middle Ages to today. In an accessible narrative that explains complex ideas in clear language, Vittorio Hösle traces the evolution of German philosophy and describes its central influence on other aspects of German culture, including literature, politics, and science.Starting with the medieval mystic Meister Eckhart, the book addresses the philosophical changes brought about by Luther's Reformation, and then presents a detailed account of the classical age of German philosophy, including the work of Leibniz and Kant; the rise of a new form of humanities in Lessing, Hamann, Herder, and Schiller; the early Romantics; and the Idealists Fichte, Schelling, and Hegel. The following chapters investigate the collapse of the German synthesis in Schopenhauer, Feuerbach, Marx, and Nietzsche. Turning to the twentieth century, the book explores the rise of analytical philosophy in Frege and the Vienna and Berlin circles; the foundation of the historical sciences in Neo-Kantianism and Dilthey; Husserl's phenomenology and its radical alteration by Heidegger; the Nazi philosophers Gehlen and Schmitt; and the main West German philosophers, including Gadamer, Jonas, and those of the two Frankfurt schools. Arguing that there was a distinctive German philosophical tradition from the mid-eighteenth century to the mid-twentieth century, the book closes by examining why that tradition largely ended in the decades after World War II.A philosophical history remarkable for its scope, brevity, and lucidity, this is an invaluable book for students of philosophy and anyone interested in German intellectual and cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aPhilosophy, GermanxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aRendall, Steven.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066753008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400883042zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400883042.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016b2016  a978-3-11-066753-0  PUP eBook-Package 2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA21UPPPUP  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN